{
  "text": "A new difficulty arises here that does not come up for s = 2, as in general g(k) does not belong to the center of G. We begin by showing that the map k → g(k) is a polynomial map from Z to G 2 (see [CITATION_1] ). The computations for this are fairly explicit and we include them.",
